I"<p>Back in autumn of 2016 I read three books about technology that left a bit of mark on me: <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Coding-Freedom-Ethics-Aesthetics-Hacking/dp/0691144613/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1479008327&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=coding+freedom"><em>Coding Freedom</em></a>, <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Cathedral-Bazaar-Musings-Accidental-Revolutionary/dp/0596001088/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1479008290&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=cathedral+bazaar"><em>Code and Other Laws of Cyberspace</em></a>, and <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Cathedral-Bazaar-Musings-Accidental-Revolutionary/dp/0596001088/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1479008290&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=cathedral+bazaar"><em>The Cathedral and the Bazaar</em></a>.</p>
